          "title": "Prologue The Brave New World of Elastic Money Mankind has us",
          "content": "In this prologue, we will explore the captivating journey of money over the last 2,500 years. For most of human history, money has been made from valuable materials, particularly gold and silver. These precious metals have special qualities that make them excellent choices for money. For instance, they are durable, meaning they can last a long time without wearing out. They are also divisible, which means they can be broken down into smaller parts without losing their value. Additionally, gold and silver are relatively scarce; there isn't an endless supply of them. This scarcity means that, unlike the money we use today, which can be created easily and in large amounts, the amount of gold and silver available is limited and cannot be increased quickly. This characteristic of being inelastic has significantly influenced how different societies have used money throughout history. In the past, the supply of money was often fixed, which meant that it could not be easily adjusted to meet the needs of the economy. However, in our modern world, we use a very different type of money. Understanding this transformation from commodity money, like gold and silver, to the paper and digital currencies we use today is essential for comprehending the current economic landscape. This shift has not only changed how we think about money but also how economies function globally. As we delve deeper into this topic, we will uncover the implications of these changes and how they affect our daily lives and the world around us.\nContext recap: In this prologue, we will explore the captivating journey of money over the last 2,500 years. For most of human history, money has been made from valuable materials, particularly gold and silver. These precious metals have special qualities that make them excellent choices for money. For instance, they are durable, meaning they can last a long time without wearing out.\nWhy this matters: Prologue The Brave New World of Elastic Money Mankind has us helps learners in Economics connect ideas from Paper Money Collapse to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
